text:
<@UR3A94N4R> I LOVE your question, because I spend a lot of time thinking about how to reconcile SEO with high-quality writing

I wrote <https://www.animalz.co/blog/copycat-content/|another article> on exactly this topic which sums up my response:

> _"It’s easy to assume that the current SERP represents the best strategy to match search intent and rank for a target keyword. It doesn't. It represents the best strategy so far._
> 
> _Seeing a search dominated by round-up articles might mean that round-ups are the optimum way to meet the search intent—it may also mean that a better type of content simply hasn't been tried."_
there was a time when ultimate guides and listicles represented a genuine improvement over most of the web's content, because it consolidated useful information into an easy-to-digest format

but today every single site copies the same format. so we're now in a situation when differentiating from all those ultimate guides -  that low concept content - is one of the best ways to stand-out from the competition and claim better rankings

you still have to answer the searcher's question and match their search intent, but you don't have to do it in a boring and utilitarian way :slightly_smiling_face:
